Don’t let the doubters, the haters, those who are miserable with their own life hijack yours!!!

Surround yourself with people who LOVE YOU (not who see you as a project) - let them speak life into you…

(Disclaimer:  The caption on the picture is 100% click bait - would strongly recommend reading the post before leaving a comment!)

Yep - it’s time for Dabo to go…

…but before I finish that statement - let’s take a stroll down memory lane!!

Anyone remember the days of Tommy West?

In his five years at Clemson his record was 31-28 and he had 1 bowl win (and we never finished ranked in the top 25 under his leadership!)

Then there was Tommy Bowden - who in 9 1/2 years took the team 73-45, three bowl wins and one time had us ranked 16 at the end of the season!

And then there was Dabo!

He had so many doubters…people who said he could not get the job done!

And yet since he took over he has gone 160-38 with 11 bowl wins, 7 ACC titles and 2 National Championships!!

(And has had the Tigers ranked in the top 15 since 2011)

So back to those saying he must go!

You are so right - and - I have no doubt he will go…

…back to his office and figure out what to do next! (He always seems to figure it out!)

Back to the phone to call mentors and leaders to help him see things he doesn’t see!

Dabo isn’t perfect - but he has always been hungry - tenacious - not willing to give up!

And so - he WILL go (like he always does) - learn, get better - and it will show in the weeks/months ahead!

For those calling for him to actually be gone - I would say that is a bit idiotic!!! 

15-20 years ago Clemson fans would have given anything to have what we have now!

So - instead of trying to throw him out - let’s let him do what he’s paid to do - coach/lead!

I have zero doubt he will figure it out and get us back in the playoffs before we know it!!!

Had to break out the gingerbread jacket to make this special announcement about @thesecondchancechurch this weekend!!

It happens once every 7 years...

...Christmas Day is on a Sunday...

...and some in the Christian community lose their minds and begin to fight over whether or not churches should actually have church on Sunday, or move their services to either Friday or Saturday. 

And so during the time of year where we should be celebrating the birth of Jesus - some choose to fight over the day we should actually do it! 

However, the purpose of this article isn't to start a fight (although I seem to have "a gift" for occasionally stirring things up) - but rather to communicate how we will be celebrating Christmas this year at Second Chance. 

Our Christmas services (which are going to be AMAZING) will be on Saturday at 2, 4 and 6pm

There will be no "in person" services on Sunday (however, the Christmas service will be available across all our social media channels that day!) 

The reason we are choosing to not have church on Sunday is...

1 - There is not an actual Biblical mandate on the exact day a church has to meet. (In other words, it's an open handed issue!) 

2 - We really want our staff and volunteers to be able to celebrate Christmas with our church...AND enjoy time with their family, and this gives us the best way to do so. 

Christmas is that time of the year when our friends and family who do not attend church are way more open to a personal invite (WAY more so than any other time of the year!) 

So - let's get the word out and get as many people as possible to a service, I can promise you that It's going to be the best Christmas service we've ever had...

...and there isn't a doubt in my mind that so many people are going to give their lives to Christ!

Over the past month or so I’ve had a few, “Hey Pastor P, why you always trying to show off your arms” and, “why are you always posting your workouts” comments/questions…

Three main reasons…

1 - Nearly 7 years ago when my life fell apart - one of the things that became very apparent was that I was not healthy physically!

No one in my family really ever has been!

Diabetes and high blood pressure on my dads side - heart disease on my moms side…

So - I did not “hit” the genetic lottery!

I understood if anyone was going to do anything about it - it was going to have to be me!

So, instead of making excuses I went to work - and can testify that being physically healthy has more benefits than I can mention is this post!

2 - Posting my workout/run every single day is an accountability hack for me!

I know there are people that, if I didn’t post a run or workout for a few days in a row - they would send out a search party for me!

(And I don’t wanna say, “Yeah, I was just lazy!” Posting keeps me motivated!)

3 - This last one is a bit crazy - but is also true!

I live in Anderson, SC - have lived here since 1990!

And - unfortunately - because of what happened in my life - I STILL hear rumors that I am getting drunk almost every night and have not changed at all! (Literally heard this last week!)

So - when I post pics like today - it’s basically giving the finger to the rumors out there!

Because - you can’t be “in shape” at (almost 52) years old while still getting hammered every single day!

This might not be the most pure motive for posting - but - there are people that follow me who won’t speak to me (hi guys!!!)…

…and I just want them to know that the Lord really is bringing some incredible changes about in my life (in every area!)

And last reason - well - my arms are not where I want them yet - but the fact is - no one gave them to me, they were not surgically implanted…

…I worked hard for them - so - when then suns out - then gotta have the guns out!

Every time I see something like this - it reminds me to keep asking Jesus to let me see people the way He sees people…

…that prayer is an absolute game changer!

If there is someone I do not particularly care for…

I don’t visit their social media sites!

I don’t create “fake accounts” so people won’t really know I am watching them!

I don’t troll them by dropping negative, hate filled comments on them!

I simply don’t visit their sites!

And - if I did - well - that would be insane!

Think about it - to go to a site that you know will make you angry and cause you to try and start a fight..

…why would anyone do that to themselves…

…unless they are an addict!

Hmmmm…let’s see…

1 - Doing something that you know is going to hurt you (long term)

2 - Trying to hide what you are doing (secret accounts)

3 - Living for the moment (leaving and checking comments) rather than enjoying the totality of life the Lord has blessed you with! (Home, family, etc!)

All this to say - if you have a “hater” that always seems to show up…its probably not you at all!

Don’t let their hate take your eyes off of what the Lord wants us to appreciate!!!

(And remember - that “block user” button is a gift from the Lord!)

I told someone this recently and they were a bit shocked!

They told me they figured the more I did it, the less nervous I would become!

But - the opposite is true (which is why I actually don’t eat anything on Sunday - just drink really good protein shakes!)

I used to feel ashamed about this!

I heard a really famous pastor say once that the reason we get nervous is because we don’t trust in the Lord.

Another one said it’s because we are not prepared!

But - I really do trust in the Lord - and I really do put a lot of work into each message!

I’ve wrestled with the “why” (about getting nervous) for years…

…and then a couple of weeks ago I heard someone say, “the reason you are nervous is because you care!”

BOOM!!!!

That SO resonated with me! 

Preaching (for me) is loving God’s Word and loving people so much…

…that I really do care about people allowing God’s Word to impact their lives!

This being said - I hope I always get nervous!!

And for those @thesecondchancechurch - thank You for letting this incredibly nervous guy preach every Sunday!
Seriously, try out a 5:00PM service this Sunday. You will not be disappointed.

If this were true - and we could handle everything that came our way, then we would never fully understand our need…

…for His strength…

…for His wisdom…

When life feels like it’s giving us more than we can handle - it’s often an indication we need to humble ourselves, acknowledge we can’t do it alone - and ask Jesus for help!
